WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.800
Thank you all for taking some time out of your day to be with us. Really looking forward

00:00:09.800 --> 00:00:17.000
to talking about dashboard fatigue and how to avoid it. And then just to reiterate what

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:22.120
Rob said, because it's always our perennial question, the recording will be available.

00:00:22.120 --> 00:00:26.440
And then we're going to be going through some slides as well as some code today. That's

00:00:26.440 --> 00:00:31.879
available already. If you want to go to this link to follow along, it's a GitHub repository

00:00:31.879 --> 00:00:38.560
that has the slides as well as the code. So dashboard fatigue, what are we talking about?

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:44.279
Before we can address kind of that question, we actually need to take a step back and think

00:00:44.279 --> 00:00:50.200
for just a second about what the goals of a data science team really are. And at the

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:55.439
end of the day, at RStudio, we believe that the main objective of a data science team

00:00:55.439 --> 00:01:00.480
is to help organizations and individuals make better decisions that are informed by

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:07.919
data. And so that's a really admirable goal, but it comes with its set of challenges. And

00:01:07.919 --> 00:01:13.199
one of the challenges that we've seen time and time again is that there's often a gap

00:01:13.199 --> 00:01:19.000
between data scientists and those stakeholders they're hoping to inform. And that gap a lot

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:25.080
of times is the result of different mediums. So data scientists can be discovering insight,

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:32.879
writing code in R, Python, whereas decision makers often are spending their time either

00:01:32.879 --> 00:01:41.199
in meetings or in their inbox or perhaps within spreadsheets. And more and more so, they're

00:01:41.199 --> 00:01:46.760
doing all of that kind of on the go as they take care of a thousand things at once, often

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:51.559
on their phone. And so for data scientists and data science teams, we have to find a

00:01:51.639 --> 00:01:59.160
way to bridge that gap so that our analysis can still be engaging and inform and ultimately

00:01:59.160 --> 00:02:04.839
drive those decisions. And there's a few different ways that we've seen teams kind of close this

00:02:04.839 --> 00:02:12.839
gap in practice. So one way that at RStudio we're big fans of is building dashboards.

00:02:12.839 --> 00:02:21.080
And so with packages like Shiny in the R ecosystem or Dash, for example, on the Python ecosystem,

00:02:21.559 --> 00:02:27.039
you can create these interactive dashboards that are more engaging for those stakeholders.

00:02:27.039 --> 00:02:32.360
So they can explore your analysis, they can ask questions, and they can kind of have an

00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:38.240
understanding that then allows them to make better decisions. So that's one kind of practical

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:43.559
and very popular way to close that gap. Of course, there's other ways as well. A lot

00:02:43.559 --> 00:02:48.839
of time and energy has been spent explaining how data scientists can put their models into

00:02:48.839 --> 00:02:54.600
production. That often is in the form of an API so that other systems and services

00:02:54.600 --> 00:03:00.600
can help take advantage of those insights. And then sometimes here we might resort to

00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:07.960
doing things like modifying PowerPoint presentations or copying and pasting results in kind of

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:14.279
more manual ways. So these are all different ways that data science teams can bridge that

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:21.399
gap between mediums to make their work more accessible to decision makers. But what we've

00:03:21.399 --> 00:03:27.320
seen is that sometimes, especially for those really awesome, interesting, exciting dashboards,

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:33.080
data science teams can fall victims to their own success. And so what do I mean by that?

00:03:33.080 --> 00:03:39.160
Well, a few weeks ago on Twitter, Angela Bassa, who leads the data science team at iRobot,

00:03:39.160 --> 00:03:45.479
they make those robotic vacuum cleaners, she asked this question on Twitter. She basically

00:03:45.479 --> 00:03:50.119
said, how do you keep track of all of your dashboards? And this led to a really interesting

00:03:50.119 --> 00:03:56.600
kind of exchange that I want to show just a few of the responses that she got. So one response

00:03:56.600 --> 00:04:02.839
is that you could go about making a dashboard of all the dashboards, so kind of a meta dashboard.

00:04:03.559 --> 00:04:08.759
And this was actually the most popular response to the threat, a very kind of data science way

00:04:08.759 --> 00:04:15.479
of thinking about solving this problem. Maybe I can use the same hammer that I used to solve the

00:04:15.479 --> 00:04:21.079
original problem and just make more dashboards. Another answer was this one I found pretty

00:04:21.079 --> 00:04:29.160
interesting. A lot of teams will create kind of an index of the work. Maybe that is a spreadsheet

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:35.160
with links to dashboards. Maybe it's a page on like Confluence or SharePoint. And of course,

00:04:35.239 --> 00:04:39.320
the challenge there is that you have to hope that you remember to keep it updated.

00:04:40.839 --> 00:04:45.959
And then I think this answer was probably the most honest, which is that a lot of times,

00:04:45.959 --> 00:04:51.480
there's not a great response. Data science teams can produce all of these interesting dashboards,

00:04:51.480 --> 00:04:58.119
but there's no great way for others to interact and keep track of them. And ultimately,

00:04:58.119 --> 00:05:05.079
this is a problem because it kind of impairs our ability as data scientists to close that

00:05:05.079 --> 00:05:11.480
gap and inform those decisions. Often what we'll see is a really great dashboard will be created

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:18.279
and users will engage with it once. But over time, in the coming days, weeks, and months,

00:05:18.839 --> 00:05:23.480
the dashboard falls by the wayside, especially if there's many of these dashboards. It's just

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:29.559
a pretty big burden to ask for your decision makers every day to go play around with the

00:05:29.559 --> 00:05:34.600
dashboard to keep track of what's going on. And so that creates a problem for us is that

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:39.079
if we just wait for decision makers to proactively go visit our work, we're not

00:05:39.079 --> 00:05:43.959
actually closing that gap. But that's one problem. We also see something else kind of

00:05:43.959 --> 00:05:51.559
interesting happen as data science teams try to close this gap. And so one thing, as we said,

00:05:51.559 --> 00:05:55.799
is that maybe the dashboards fall by the wayside. Another thing that can often happen

00:05:55.799 --> 00:06:00.839
is that stakeholders will get excited. They'll say, great, this insight makes sense.

00:06:00.839 --> 00:06:07.559
Can you bring it to my medium? Can you copy and paste those predictions into my spreadsheet?

00:06:07.559 --> 00:06:11.959
Or can you send me a screenshot of that plot so I can put it in my presentation?

00:06:12.600 --> 00:06:17.720
And that leads to a lot of painful, labor-intensive work. One of the interesting

00:06:17.720 --> 00:06:21.480
things over the last couple of months is that I got to work at home with my wife,

00:06:21.480 --> 00:06:26.920
who is also an R user. And one day, looking over her shoulder, we kind of had this exchange

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:31.720
where she was doing exactly what I just described. She was taking the results of some R code and

00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:37.239
plugging them into a spreadsheet for her boss. And me, being the RStudio fanboy, kind of said,

00:06:37.239 --> 00:06:40.760
why don't you create a Shiny app? That'd be really awesome. It'd save you all this time.

00:06:41.640 --> 00:06:47.480
And it could be a big win for your organization. And I wish I could have captured the look

00:06:47.480 --> 00:06:54.040
on my wife's face in her response here. What she basically said was, my boss, Dave,

00:06:54.040 --> 00:07:00.200
has been looking at the same spreadsheet every week for years. Any one who tries to make changes

00:07:00.200 --> 00:07:08.040
gets decimated, basically. And so she was kind of stuck in this equally problematic scenario.

00:07:08.040 --> 00:07:12.679
I mean, at least her boss was engaging with her work. But it was in a way that

00:07:12.679 --> 00:07:17.399
was really killing her productivity. We often refer to these as fire drills, where you have to

00:07:17.799 --> 00:07:21.880
answer ad hoc questions that require a lot of manual, labor-intensive work,

00:07:22.440 --> 00:07:26.839
especially on the formatting side, if you're copying and pasting results into different mediums.

00:07:28.200 --> 00:07:34.279
And so to summarize the intro here briefly, data science teams often can find themselves

00:07:34.279 --> 00:07:40.679
trying to thread this challenging needle, where on the one hand, you might put a lot of effort

00:07:40.679 --> 00:07:45.399
into something really awesome, like a dashboard, only to see that it kind of falls by the wayside.

00:07:45.399 --> 00:07:50.359
On the other hand, you spend all of your time kind of in these manual, ad hoc fire drills.

00:07:51.399 --> 00:07:56.600
Neither of those are great ways to, in the long run, close that gap between data scientists and

00:07:56.600 --> 00:08:04.440
decision makers. But I'd like to propose for you today an alternative, a solution that we've found

00:08:04.440 --> 00:08:10.359
a lot of success using ourselves here at RStudio. And so what does this solution entail? Instead of

00:08:10.359 --> 00:08:17.799
creating a dashboard, what we like to do is create a proactive notifier, or something that

00:08:17.799 --> 00:08:24.279
is going to alert me to the information that I need to know. And in our case, we spend most of

00:08:24.279 --> 00:08:29.160
our time inside of our inboxes, so that's where our alerts goes, is through email. But we still

00:08:29.160 --> 00:08:35.320
want to be able to do that as data scientists writing code. And so that's what we're going to

00:08:35.320 --> 00:08:42.440
talk about today, is how you can use a rich set of R packages to allow you to create these

00:08:42.440 --> 00:08:48.280
proactive notifications. And as I mentioned, kind of with my wife's dilemma, oftentimes these

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:53.080
notifications need to meet the expectations of our stakeholders for how they're formatted.

00:08:53.080 --> 00:08:58.039
So we'll look at some new packages that are available to help you precisely format these

00:08:58.039 --> 00:09:03.799
results. And then finally, we don't want to solve this dashboard fatigue problem by introducing

00:09:03.799 --> 00:09:08.679
another type of fatigue, which would be email fatigue. And so we're going to talk about how

00:09:09.799 --> 00:09:16.599
you can only send these alerts on conditions, so that instead of sending emails every day,

00:09:17.479 --> 00:09:22.520
you can send emails more specifically when there's a problem at hand. And then finally,

00:09:23.159 --> 00:09:26.679
we've been talking a lot about fatigue. We don't want to introduce email fatigue, dashboard

00:09:26.679 --> 00:09:30.119
fatigue. We also don't want to introduce data science fatigue. So we're going to talk about

00:09:30.119 --> 00:09:35.400
how we can achieve these proactive notifications in an automated way, so that someone doesn't have

00:09:35.400 --> 00:09:41.320
to click play every morning. The picture that you're seeing here is one of my favorite examples

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:47.159
of this workflow. One of my roles at RStudio is to keep track of all the different R packages that we

00:09:47.719 --> 00:09:53.719
build and maintain. For some of you on the line, R packages might be a newer thing. So briefly,

00:09:54.359 --> 00:10:00.039
they're just basically extensions of the R ecosystem. They're sort of the bread and butter

00:10:00.039 --> 00:10:04.919
of how data science gets done in R. They're also one of the main things that we're responsible for

00:10:04.919 --> 00:10:10.200
at RStudio, is creating these different R packages. And so every day, we go and we build

00:10:10.200 --> 00:10:16.679
all of these packages. And we want to know if any of those builds fail, especially if it's

00:10:16.679 --> 00:10:22.840
a really popular package. We don't want to get a whole bunch of emails from users saying, hey,

00:10:22.840 --> 00:10:27.400
this package isn't available or doesn't work. We kind of want to stay ahead of those types of

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:32.760
problems. And so what a data scientist named Greg and I came up with is this workflow,

00:10:32.760 --> 00:10:37.080
where every day we run these builds. And then if there's a problem, and critically,

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:41.880
only if there's a problem, do we get these types of targeted emails that tell me exactly what the

00:10:41.880 --> 00:10:48.119
problem was, and allow me to then take further action. And an example of that email from my

00:10:48.119 --> 00:10:54.359
inbox is what you're seeing on the screen. We're not the only ones who are kind of using

00:10:54.359 --> 00:10:59.159
this pattern successfully. So I just want to tell you a few quick stories before we get into the

00:10:59.159 --> 00:11:05.320
weeds of writing the code. One of my favorite stories is from a large infrastructure as a

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:11.159
service provider. So a company that maintains thousands, if not hundreds of thousands of servers.

00:11:11.880 --> 00:11:18.840
And what they use this workflow to do was track their hardware uptime. And then if they saw a

00:11:18.840 --> 00:11:24.760
problem arising, they could send a proactive alert out to their vendors in the context of their

00:11:24.760 --> 00:11:30.599
support level agreement, or SLA. And what this team was really excited about is before adopting this

00:11:30.599 --> 00:11:36.200
workflow, they had done this type of task in JIRA. And any time they onboarded a new vendor or they

00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:42.039
modified their SLA, they had to manually click through a whole bunch of steps in JIRA to accomplish

00:11:42.599 --> 00:11:48.039
this task. The great thing about this workflow is that it's all based on code. So it's really easy

00:11:48.039 --> 00:11:53.080
to reuse these different rules and different markdown documents that you're going to write.

00:11:53.960 --> 00:11:57.719
And so this allowed the team to easily cut down their onboarding time.

00:11:59.320 --> 00:12:05.559
Another really awesome story of this type of technology applied was in a high-tech manufacturer

00:12:05.559 --> 00:12:10.599
People Ops Department, so kind of an HR group. And they had this challenging task where they

00:12:10.599 --> 00:12:18.039
needed to notify division managers about employee overtime problems. So say an employee worked more

00:12:18.039 --> 00:12:23.559
overtime than they were allowed, they wanted to send out an alert. Now before, they had a dashboard.

00:12:23.559 --> 00:12:28.840
And what they found was there are 30 different division managers were not reliably going to that

00:12:28.840 --> 00:12:34.840
dashboard every day to check if there was problems. And so they adopted this workflow to instead

00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:40.359
send out an email to a manager only if there was actually a problem with a specific employee's

00:12:40.359 --> 00:12:46.440
overtime submission. And they actually won an award of excellence for adopting this workflow,

00:12:46.440 --> 00:12:51.400
which I think is really exciting because it's ultimately a pretty simple concept that we're

00:12:51.400 --> 00:12:55.960
talking about here. And so if they're able to win excellence awards, I think that's going to be

00:12:55.960 --> 00:13:01.799
accessible to a lot of teams as well. So let's get into the nuts and bolts a little bit to set

00:13:01.799 --> 00:13:05.479
the stage for Rich, who's going to walk you through the code here. I just want to talk about

00:13:05.479 --> 00:13:09.320
the different tools in our tool belt that are going to allow us to apply this workflow.

00:13:10.599 --> 00:13:16.200
And so the first thing that I mentioned is that we're going to be crafting emails. And to do that

00:13:16.200 --> 00:13:21.960
we're going to use two R packages. The first one is R Markdown. If you're not familiar with R Markdown,

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:28.599
it's a package that allows you to combine code and text to create documents, beautifully

00:13:28.919 --> 00:13:35.400
kind of customizable documents. And so historically R Markdown has been used to create

00:13:35.400 --> 00:13:42.599
PDF files or HTML files. But in our case, we want to use R Markdown for is creating the actual

00:13:42.599 --> 00:13:49.239
body of an email. It turns out an email's body is kind of unique and different from other types of

00:13:49.239 --> 00:13:54.919
output formats. And so to help kind of adjust R Markdown to create the body of an email,

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:59.880
we've introduced a new package called Blastula. And so that's what Blastula is really good at,

00:13:59.880 --> 00:14:07.559
is helping you craft the body of your email. We also mentioned that often when you implement

00:14:07.559 --> 00:14:13.559
these types of workflows, you need to format results in a very specific way. And because of

00:14:13.559 --> 00:14:19.080
kind of the legacy of spreadsheets, that very specific format tends to be a table. And so we're

00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:24.280
going to spend a little bit of time walking you through GT, which is a package that allows you to

00:14:24.280 --> 00:14:30.359
have a lot of control over the types of tables that you can produce from R. And it's also

00:14:30.359 --> 00:14:35.880
compatible with Blastula and R Markdown. So you can embed those tables right into the email,

00:14:35.880 --> 00:14:42.840
like you saw in my example. So those are kind of the packages. And then we get to what I think is

00:14:42.840 --> 00:14:48.919
really the heart of this whole solution, which is how we can send these types of notifications

00:14:48.919 --> 00:14:54.840
in a more dynamic way on a condition. And the amazing thing about writing code is that

00:14:54.840 --> 00:15:00.520
our answer here for what can our condition be is really endless. With code, the answer is always

00:15:00.520 --> 00:15:07.559
yes. That is really true here. Your condition might be something like anomaly detection.

00:15:07.559 --> 00:15:12.840
It might be a complex model that allows you to determine kind of dynamic thresholds with

00:15:12.840 --> 00:15:18.119
uncertainty levels. In our case, it's going to be just a simple set of rules. But no matter what it

00:15:18.119 --> 00:15:24.760
is, the actual implementation of sending a notification on a condition boils down to a

00:15:24.760 --> 00:15:29.960
really simple if statement that I think is kind of at the heart of how powerful this workflow can be.

00:15:31.239 --> 00:15:35.640
And then finally, I mentioned we don't want to introduce data science fatigue. So we don't want

00:15:35.640 --> 00:15:41.559
to use these tools and then still end up in a world where every day we have to press play on

00:15:41.559 --> 00:15:46.039
rendering these reports and sending out these alerts. And so we're going to talk a little bit

00:15:46.039 --> 00:15:51.640
about how to automate this workflow. Now, there's a lot of open source ways that you could go about

00:15:51.640 --> 00:15:58.440
doing this. You could use something as simple as CronTab to manage the execution of these reports.

00:15:58.440 --> 00:16:03.559
Or perhaps you could use a more advanced scheduler, something like Airflow. But in our case,

00:16:03.559 --> 00:16:08.280
we're going to look at RStudio Connect, which is a professional product that RStudio kind of sells.

00:16:09.239 --> 00:16:15.159
And what RStudio Connect does really well is it takes care of some of the intricacies

00:16:15.159 --> 00:16:19.400
of putting R into production. So you don't have to worry about the different packages

00:16:19.400 --> 00:16:25.000
that your report might need. You don't have to worry about logging failures, about authenticating

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:31.159
users, about securely sending email, or scaling out the system. And so it's a really powerful way

00:16:31.159 --> 00:16:35.400
to kind of adopt a lot of these automation features without having to reinvent them all

00:16:35.400 --> 00:16:40.599
yourselves. So that's what we're going to show you today. But the key to all of this, I think,

00:16:40.599 --> 00:16:45.159
is that the code that we're going to look at is actually really fun to write. And that's

00:16:45.159 --> 00:16:51.080
important because doing something that's fun is obviously a good incentive to do it in the first

00:16:51.080 --> 00:16:55.719
place, but also makes it easier to share these types of workflows amongst your organization

00:16:55.719 --> 00:16:59.719
and to have other people kind of adopt them as well, which is critical if you want to have

00:17:00.440 --> 00:17:08.199
a critical mass around this new type of workflow. So to set the stage here for Rich, this is what

00:17:08.199 --> 00:17:11.560
we're going to walk through in our demo. We're going to start with some fake data,

