people that are designated to see it. And so, there are some security ramifications when you

00:40:44.520 --> 00:40:49.000
get into the realm of automating notifications that you'll just want to be careful of if you're

00:40:49.879 --> 00:40:52.120
integrating with one of those other options yourself.

00:40:55.879 --> 00:41:01.719
Let's see, in terms of other interesting questions, Swanet asked a pretty interesting one,

00:41:01.719 --> 00:41:07.320
which is, you know, do you have to use R or is there a way to incorporate other languages like

00:41:07.320 --> 00:41:15.560
Python into these types of workflows? I'm sure there's a way, but the thing you're missing is

00:41:15.560 --> 00:41:23.560
like Blastula for, you know, creating the email message body. And Python does have, it might,

00:41:23.560 --> 00:41:30.840
you know, I've looked around and I've looked for other Python libraries that do this sort of thing,

00:41:30.840 --> 00:41:35.239
like create email. And certainly, you can send an email right through Python, but the hard part

00:41:35.239 --> 00:41:40.840
is creating a message body. And even harder part is creating an HTML message body, which is what

00:41:40.840 --> 00:41:47.320
Blastula does. So, I think it's possible. You just have to do a lot of upfront work. You basically

00:41:47.320 --> 00:41:55.479
have to reproduce Blastula in Python to get that going. I'd love to find out if there are any other

00:41:55.479 --> 00:42:00.040
packages, or sorry, libraries in Python that actually do what Blastula does. But in my search,

00:42:00.040 --> 00:42:07.159
I couldn't find it. I'll add to that, Rich. One kind of way that you could combine these two

00:42:07.159 --> 00:42:15.000
together is actually within R Markdown. And so, it's a bit of a misnomer, but R Markdown allows

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:20.120
you to combine a whole bunch of different languages. So, while it's an R Markdown document,

00:42:20.120 --> 00:42:25.639
you can certainly have Python code chunks commingled with R code chunks, commingled with

00:42:25.959 --> 00:42:31.479
bash code chunks, if you want it, or SQL. And so, all those different languages can live inside

00:42:31.479 --> 00:42:40.360
the R Markdown document. And then R, and that type of workflow just becomes a facilitator for

00:42:40.360 --> 00:42:46.840
sending the email using Rich's awesome work on Blastula. Yeah, I'm glad you brought that up.

00:42:46.840 --> 00:42:51.000
Because yeah, definitely all the other stuff you can do in R Markdown. It has a lot of engines

00:42:51.080 --> 00:42:55.159
available. But the last piece is kind of critical.

00:42:58.919 --> 00:43:05.159
So, this is kind of an interesting question, Rich, on a little bit more kind of philosophical,

00:43:05.159 --> 00:43:11.239
I guess. The person asks, how is this approach influencing kind of your thinking around

00:43:11.239 --> 00:43:16.520
dashboards and kind of when you would use a dashboard and when you wouldn't?

00:43:17.479 --> 00:43:24.600
Ah, yeah, a dashboard, it's still pretty essential. But I wouldn't use it as a way to

00:43:24.600 --> 00:43:29.800
notify people of anything important, right? Because it involves diligence and seeing the

00:43:29.800 --> 00:43:37.000
dashboards daily or whichever frequency is required to be ahead of important issues.

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:43.159
So, a dashboard is part of the whole thing. You can go to a dashboard once you get notified,

00:43:43.159 --> 00:43:49.239
and then get the history of what led to certain problems up to the present day or whatever.

00:43:50.360 --> 00:43:52.520
It's not a replacement for a dashboard. It's basically, this

00:43:53.399 --> 00:44:01.560
basically adds to the whole stack of analytics. And one thing I'll echo there that also kind of

00:44:01.560 --> 00:44:07.479
addresses another question that was asked. We kind of touched on this very briefly. But a common

00:44:07.479 --> 00:44:14.280
pattern in those emails that you send is to dynamically generate a link back to a dashboard.

00:44:14.280 --> 00:44:18.840
And so, something that we do a lot at RStudio, in the example I mentioned at the beginning,

00:44:18.840 --> 00:44:24.120
I'll get an email that says, hey, these packages failed to build. And then it includes a link to

00:44:24.120 --> 00:44:30.840
a dashboard where I can explore like the error codes and the duration of the job and all sorts

00:44:30.840 --> 00:44:36.040
of more kind of interactive questions. And so, dashboards aren't out of the picture.

00:44:36.040 --> 00:44:40.360
They just, as Rich said, aren't the mechanism for doing the notification.

00:44:41.560 --> 00:44:42.520
Yeah, exactly.

00:44:45.719 --> 00:44:51.879
There was a question here, instead of hard coding the thresholds, they can be dynamic, right?

00:44:52.760 --> 00:44:53.399
Yes, absolutely.

00:44:53.399 --> 00:44:53.959
Of course.

00:44:53.959 --> 00:44:57.719
This is basically your code. I just basically whipped something up together.

00:44:58.360 --> 00:45:03.159
Very unsophisticated, whether it's below or above. You can definitely pull in data,

00:45:03.159 --> 00:45:08.199
generate the thresholds dynamically, compare. There's lots of ways to do this. You can use

00:45:08.199 --> 00:45:15.959
packages like anomaly detection, or you can use like the forecast package to do certain things.

00:45:15.959 --> 00:45:20.600
Essentially, what you want to do is you want to get to a place where you can make a final decision

00:45:20.600 --> 00:45:26.199
on whether to send the email or not, and then what to put in that email. And you may have

00:45:26.199 --> 00:45:31.639
different versions of email. You may select between different types, or you may be more

00:45:31.639 --> 00:45:37.000
sophisticated in the dynamic content. You include like a subject line or even content in email,

00:45:38.040 --> 00:45:42.280
because the variables are transmitted from the main document to the sub-document,

00:45:42.280 --> 00:45:48.439
which is kind of cool. So yeah, basically, because this is code, you can do whatever you want.

00:45:48.439 --> 00:45:51.159
You can go nuts, essentially.

00:45:52.040 --> 00:46:02.520
Yeah, a kind of follow-on question. It was, maybe as a data scientist, I don't know the triggers or

00:46:02.520 --> 00:46:06.840
thresholds. And so the question was, does it always fall on the data science team to set them,

00:46:06.840 --> 00:46:10.199
or is there some way for decision makers to influence the thresholds?

00:46:12.040 --> 00:46:19.399
Yeah, that sort of thing. I think it's a conversation between the data team and the decision

00:46:19.959 --> 00:46:25.399
makers in the organization, for sure. You may come up with a set of recommendations. You may

00:46:25.399 --> 00:46:31.080
change them on a weekly basis or some other frequency. It may be dynamic. It may just be a

00:46:31.080 --> 00:46:36.439
system which creates thresholds if values are changing fast, right, and there's seasonality

00:46:36.439 --> 00:46:41.000
or things like that. So it really depends on the organization. But essentially, it should be

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:45.719
transparent, I think, because decision makers are getting the notification. They probably should

00:46:45.719 --> 00:46:55.239
know why. And yeah, basically, it's a conversation. Yep. And the nice thing about

00:46:56.120 --> 00:47:02.520
code is that it's not a black box. It's very inspectable, and it gives you the full flexibility

00:47:02.520 --> 00:47:06.919
there. So you're not locked in. It's not like RStudio's deciding what the threshold should be

00:47:06.919 --> 00:47:15.879
for you. You get all the options there. And that kind of leads to another question that came up

00:47:15.879 --> 00:47:21.959
that I thought was really awesome. We talked a lot in this webinar about creating notifications

00:47:22.679 --> 00:47:28.919
to bridge the gap between data scientists and decision makers. But this person asked,

00:47:28.919 --> 00:47:35.239
could the same workflow apply to notify the data science team of data quality issues?

00:47:36.199 --> 00:47:42.520
Absolutely. Yeah. Yeah, definitely. Yeah. I mean, it's totally up to you who the email's

00:47:42.520 --> 00:47:50.439
directed to. I would set up diagnostic emails to yourself, if important. If certain data

00:47:52.280 --> 00:47:58.679
is suspect based on some data validation rules that you have, I would want to know about it.

00:47:58.679 --> 00:48:04.040
And then I would want to let data engineering know about it, too, to get at the root cause of things.

00:48:04.840 --> 00:48:11.560
So absolutely, yeah. Definitely send yourself these notifications. Yeah, that's my pitch.

00:48:12.679 --> 00:48:18.439
So those were some high level questions. There's a few more in the weeds questions

00:48:19.560 --> 00:48:24.520
that we'll address here at the end. One of them is from someone who's

00:48:24.520 --> 00:48:32.360
already playing around with the code. So kudos to you. And they've hit a stumbling block that

00:48:32.520 --> 00:48:39.239
is maybe a little bit common as you're learning this workflow. And rather than reading the question

00:48:39.239 --> 00:48:44.679
verbatim, Rich, I'll basically diagnose it. And maybe you could even show the workflow here.

00:48:44.679 --> 00:48:50.439
But essentially what they did was they rendered the child document instead of the main document.

00:48:50.439 --> 00:48:54.360
So can you talk a little bit about which document to render and when?

00:48:54.360 --> 00:48:58.360
Yeah. So this is a trap I always fall into, because it doesn't stop you from rendering

00:48:58.360 --> 00:49:01.879
the child document. So it's always the main document. So if you render the child document,

00:49:02.439 --> 00:49:06.360
nothing good comes from that. There should probably be a warning somewhere, but there's

00:49:06.360 --> 00:49:10.600
nowhere to put it. But essentially, it all comes from the main document. And that gives you two

00:49:10.600 --> 00:49:15.080
previews. So basically, the thing you want to ask yourself is, am I seeing two previews? And if not,

00:49:15.080 --> 00:49:20.919
I probably did something wrong. So always hit knit on the main document. And then you'll be A-OK.

00:49:21.560 --> 00:49:26.040
Otherwise, it won't harm anything. It just won't give you anything useful. It'll probably just give

00:49:26.040 --> 00:49:30.840
you something not great. Yeah. The error messages that you'll

00:49:30.840 --> 00:49:36.600
tend to see if you accidentally knit the child document are that variables are undefined. And

00:49:36.600 --> 00:49:42.120
that's because those variables are defined in your main document. Now, of course, you could

00:49:42.120 --> 00:49:47.800
duplicate all the code into the child document to have a child document that's also standalone.

00:49:47.800 --> 00:49:52.600
But then you needlessly copied and pasted code, which is something that we're always trying to

00:49:52.600 --> 00:49:59.959
avoid. Yeah. Try to keep dry, even in your email message bodies or your RMRDON documents. So people

00:49:59.959 --> 00:50:03.959
that don't know what dry means, don't repeat yourself. Try as much as possible to have one

00:50:03.959 --> 00:50:09.320
place for code. And that's the great thing about these sub-documents, taking results from the main

00:50:09.320 --> 00:50:15.479
document. You don't have to rewrite code and worry about being in sync between the documents.

00:50:18.679 --> 00:50:27.000
Excellent. And then just for the sake of being in the weeds with our audience here,

00:50:27.719 --> 00:50:35.320
maybe one final question for you, Rich. This one was related to GT, which we spoke on briefly.

00:50:35.320 --> 00:50:44.679
And they said, how would you apply the same row rules across multiple columns? And maybe you can

00:50:44.679 --> 00:50:51.320
just use this as an opportunity, Rich, to speak a little bit more towards what the philosophy is

00:50:51.320 --> 00:50:56.199
behind writing GT code and doing the types of highlighting that you demoed today.

00:50:57.000 --> 00:51:01.000
Yeah. Basically, what you're doing with highlighting is you're using tab style,

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:06.840
and you're specifying either the whole row, the whole column, or an individual cell with the

00:51:06.840 --> 00:51:11.719
locations argument. So it's basically like you're on an Excel sheet, and you're clicking something

00:51:11.719 --> 00:51:16.919
to highlight it. And then you're doing this bit of styling, which could be changing the text,

00:51:16.919 --> 00:51:22.040
changing the background of the cell, whatever. How would I apply the same thing? I would just

00:51:22.040 --> 00:51:27.879
use the columns argument and specify multiple columns within bars. That's how you normally do

00:51:27.879 --> 00:51:33.479
that. I would try that first. If it doesn't work, then it might be something a little bit more

00:51:34.120 --> 00:51:40.679
to it. And if the question is super important, I would definitely ask it in RStudio community,

00:51:40.679 --> 00:51:46.919
